  "response": "Electronic configuration is the arrangement of electrons in an atom's orbitals. Here's a step-by-step process:\n\n1. Basic Principles:\n- Electrons fill orbitals from lowest to highest energy\n- Follow Aufbau principle\n- Obey Pauli exclusion principle\n- Follow Hund's rule\n\n2. Energy Level Order:\n1s \u2192 2s \u2192 2p \u2192 3s \u2192 3p \u2192 4s \u2192 3d \u2192 4p \u2192 5s \u2192 4d \u2192 5p \u2192 6s \u2192 4f \u2192 5d \u2192 6p \u2192 7s\n\n3. Electron Filling Methods:\na) Orbital notation\n- Write sub-shells with electron count\n- Example: 1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076\n\nb) Shorthand notation\n- Use noble gas core\n- Example: [Ne] 3s\u00b9 for sodium\n\n4. Rules for Filling:\n- Maximum 2 electrons per orbital\n- Paired electrons have opposite spins\n- Half-filled orbitals preferred in some cases\n\n5. Determination Steps:\n- Identify total number of electrons\n- Follow energy level order\n- Fill orbitals systematically\n- Check final configuration\n\nExample: Carbon (6 electrons)\n1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u00b2",
